Note from Author April 23, 2026

“Since I am waiting for my weekly Claude code usage to reset at 3pm today I figured it would be appropriate to write a note here for anyone that comes across this repo.    My name is Carl Zimmerman, I’m 36 years old and live in the beautiful city of Charlotte, North Carolina with my wife and twin toddlers. A few close friends have asked me.. why were you trying to figure this out in the first place? It is a good question. 

Well, let me explain… 

My wife was out of town on a four day work trip, and after getting the kids down for bed, made the executive decision that tinkering around with Andrej Kaparthy’s new Autoresearch tool would be a lot more fun than finishing cleaning up.  The problem was I did not really have anything specific i wanted to have it do for me.. so I thought well why not try to discover some new physics?  The chances are technically non-zero, but practically speaking - zero. If anything it would be a fun way to learn some new things that I did not know before, so this project would not come at a total loss (at least that is the justification i made to myself).    Of course I used Claude Code in Android Studio to set up the autoresearch loop and gave it my intention.  It said… What an ambitious project!  Would you like me to start coming up with new ideas for the latest dark matter hyperwaveloopfluidnewparticle theory? 

I replied no. 

Before we get into all that, we need to systematically go through all the literature that was written by theoretical physicists and researchers pre theory of relativity, and individually decade by decade afterwards to make absolutely certain there was nothing overlooked that we can test empirically with the latest data from the James Web Space Telescope.    Almost all of them had either been ruled out previously without a doubt, or they did not have a way of doing any sort of computational analysis on them.  I say almost because there was one.. Moti Milgrom’s MOND theory from 1984.   Perfect. Claude go fetch me all the latest open source data you can find from JWST and SPARC and see if we can do some curve fitting that uses MOND in a way that works in both nearly galaxies and early galaxies.. a week goes by of nothing and me telling Claude to just keep going ultrathink and keep building based on what we have found so far in the process.. and then.. 

a0 = h0 / 5.79 

Hmm.. that is interesting. If we assume this is correct.. i wonder what else we can derive out of it that can either verify or falsify this claim using the scientific method?


to be continued… 
